description: Application for a Minor Material Amendment (S73) to vary Variation of condition 2 (approved drawings) of planning application ref: P/2014/6383 dated 23.10.2015 for 'Demolition of all buildings within Sherwood Close (including 209 residential units, parking structures and ancillary buildings) and the construction of 305 new residential units (88 x one-bedroom, 157 x two-bedroom, 52 x three-bedroom and 8 x four-bedroom in a mix of housing tenures) in four apartment buildings varying between two-storeys and nine-storeys high and a row of three-storey townhouses; a 70 sq .m community space (D2 Use Class); associated energy plant room; refuse and recycling facilities; storage for 410 bicycles; 122 car parking spaces (comprising 86 spaces on-street and 36 spaces in an under croft parking area); site-wide hard and soft landscaping including public, semi-private and private amenity space and public realm improvements; the closure of part of Sherwood Close and reconfiguration of the public highway including the construction of two new north-south streets between Sherwood Close and Tawny Close, and the construction of new pedestrian / cycle routes between Sherwood Close, Tawny Close and Northfield Avenue and other associated works'./ Variation seeking to reflect Minor Material Amendments to Block C4 of the development.
decision_conditions: The development permitted has already commenced in accordance with Section 56 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended). | The development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and documents:

Technical reports: Covering Letter (ref: GJ/4000) (dated 19/12/2014), prepared by Quod; Covering Letter (ref: Q80381) (dated 15/11/2017), prepared by Quod; Design and Access Statement (dated December 2014), prepared by Feilden Clegg Bradley Studios; Design and Access Statement Addendum (DAS) (dated October 2017) prepared by Feilden Clegg Bradley Studios, Buro Happold and Place; Planning Statement (ref: Q40000) (dated November 2014), prepared by Quod; Planning Statement (ref: Q80381) (dated November 2017), prepared by Quod; Statement of Community Involvement (dated November 2014), prepared by Affinity Sutton; Statement of Community Involvement Addendum (Sherwood Close - Revision to Block C4, dated October 2017), prepared by Affinity Sutton Homes Limited; Transport Assessment Addendum (ref: STHLSD25, dated 06th October 2017), prepared by Systra; Transport Assessment (ref: ST13360, Issue No. 7) (dated 11/12/2014) and drawing ST13360-20 A, prepared by JMP Consultants Ltd; (draft) Residential Travel Plan (ref: ST13360, Issue No. 6) (dated 11/12/2014), prepared by JMP Consultants Ltd; Pre-Construction Phase Site Waste Management Plan (Ref: 28075/3001) (dated 08/08/2014), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Site Waste Management Plan Addendum (ref: 28075, dated October 2017), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Draft Construction Management Plan (dated November 2014), prepared by EC Harris; Sherwood Close Energy Statement D (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham; Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessment Rev A (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham; Sustainability Statement - Block C4 (ref: J2347, dated October 2017), prepared by Mendick Waring Ltd; Sherwood Close Utilities Statement A (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham; Site Specific Arboricultural Survey & Impact Statement (dated 24/10/2014), prepared by Wassells Arboricultural Services; Tree Strategy Update - Block C4 Addendum (ref: WAS 80/2017, dated 19th October 2017), prepared by Wassells; Flood Risk Assessment (Rev 005, dated February 2015) and drawing 28075-C-SK-01 Rev P2; LBE Drainage Assessment Form (ref: 6158778, dated 31/10/2017), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Flood Risk Assessment - Block C4 Addendum (Ref: 42150/003-Rev A, dated September 2017), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Daylight & Sunlight Report (dated 10/11/2014), prepared by EB7; Daylight and Sunlight Report (Sherwood Close, dated 06th October 2017), prepared by EB7; Noise Impact Assessment Rev A (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham; Phase II Ground Investigation Report (ref: 13426/GIR) (dated June 2013), prepared by Soils Ltd; Phase 1 Ecology Site Survey (ref: 550411mtOctFV02_ Phase1_CSH_Ecology) (dated October 2014), prepared by Greengage; Air Quality Assessment (ref: 28075/002 Rev 01) (dated October 2014), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Air Quality Technical Note (ref:42150, dated 13th October 2017), prepared by Peter Brett Associates; Sherwood Close - Block Tenure Area Analysis FCBS Architects Schedule - Revision O (received 11/02/2015); MFLLP Response to Sherwood Close Planning Queries (dated 26/02/2015 and Revision A (dated 05/03/2015).
Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning.

| Prior to the commencement of development within each Phase of the development, a site construction management and logistics plan shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The submission shall include the following information:
a)            The number of on-site construction workers and details of the transport options for them;
b)            anticipated route, anticipated number, frequency and size of construction vehicles entering/exiting the site per day;
c)            delivery times and booking system;
d)            route and location of site access for construction traffic and associated signage, including provision of Banksman if Northfield Avenue is used for construction traffic;
e)            management of consolidated or re-timed trips;

f)             Details of noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures and monitoring arrangements for noise, vibration and dust by suitably qualified noise and air quality specialists.  Noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures must accord with the Mayor's SPG 'The control of dust and emissions from construction and demolition ' (2014); BS 5228 Parts 1 & 2; the Institute of Air Quality Management 'Guidance on the assessment of dust from demolition and construction'; and the recommendations contained at chapter 6 of the approved Air Quality Assessment (dated October 2014, prepared by Max Fordham;
g)            details of site security and the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate;
h)            secure, off-street loading and drop-off facilities;

i)             vehicle manoeuvring and turning, including swept path diagrams to demonstrate how construction vehicles will access the site and be able to turn into and emerge from the site in forward gear and including details of any temporary vehicle access points;
j)             details of the location for storage of building materials and construction debris and contractors offices;
k)            procedures for on-site contractors to deal with complaints from members of the public;
l)             measures to consult cyclists, disabled people and the local schools with regard  to delivery times and necessary diversions;
m)          details of all pedestrian and cyclist diversions;
n)            a commitment to be part of Considerate Constructors Scheme; and
o)            confirmation of use of TfL's Freight Operator Recognition Scheme (FORS) or similar

Prior to the commencement of any site work, all sensitive properties within or surrounding the site shall be notified in writing of the nature and duration of the works to be undertaken, and the name and address of a responsible person to whom enquiries / complaints should be directed. These details shall also be displayed at regular intervals around the site compound. The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.

Reason:  In the interests of the amenity of adjoining occupiers and to minimise highway and traffic impact during the course of the works, in accordance with policies 1.1 (e) (f) (j) of the Ealing Development (Core) Strategy 2012, policy 6.3 of the London Plan (2016) and policy 7A of the Ealing Development Management Development Plan.

| Prior to the commencement of development within each Phase of the development, a Site Waste Management Plan shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The Site Waste Management Plan shall demonstrate how the procurement of materials for the development would promote sustainability, including by use of low impact, sustainably sourced, reused and recycled materials, including reuse of demolition waste, use of local suppliers and by reference to the BRE's Green Guide Specification. The development shall be carried out in accordance with the particulars so approved.

Reason:  To ensure sustainable procurement of materials which minimises the negative environmental impacts of construction in accordance with policy 5.17 of the London Plan (2016); policy 1.1(e) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); and interim SPG 4: Refuse and Recycling Facilities.

| No development shall commence in relation to each Phase of development (including demolition, site clearance and preparation works) until an Arboricultural Method Statement (AMS) prepared in accordance with BS 5837:2012 'Trees in Relation to Design, Demolition and Construction' has been submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The details of the retention and removal of trees must be consistent with the details set out in the approved 'Site Specific Arboricultural Survey & Impact Statement', prepared by Wassells Arbricultural Services (dated 24/10/2014), Tree Strategy Update: Block C4 Addendum (October 2017), Design and Access Statement, prepared by Fielden Clegg Bradley Studios (dated December 2014) and Design and Access Statement Addendum (October 2017).

All protection measures must fully detail each phase of the development process taking into account demolition / site clearance works, all construction works and hard and soft landscaping works.  Details shall include the following:

a)      Full survey of the hedgerow located along the Northfield Avenue (east) boundary and all trees on site and those within influencing distance on adjacent sites in accordance with BS5837*,  with tree works proposals.  All trees must be plotted on a site plan**, clearly and accurately depicting trunk locations, root protection areas and canopy spreads.
b)      A plan** detailing all trees, shrubs, hedges planned for retention and removal.
c)      Soil assessments/survey
d)      Timing and phasing of works
e)      Site specific demolition and hard surface removal specifications
f)       Site specific construction specifications
g)      Access arrangements and car parking
h)      Level changes

i)       A Tree protection plan** in accordance with BS5837* detailing all methods of protection, including but not restricted to: locations of construction exclusion zones, root protection areas, fit for purpose fencing and ground protection, service routes, works access space, material/machinery/waste storage and permanent & temporary hard surfaces.
j)        Soil remediation plans.

The tree protection measures shall be in place prior to the commencement of the development and retained until the development has been completed. The areas enclosed by the tree protection measures shall not be used for any storage and the levels within these areas shall not be altered.

All hedgerow and tree protection methods detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement shall not be moved or removed, temporarily or otherwise, until all works including external works have been completed and all equipment, machinery and surplus materials have been removed from the  site, unless the prior approval of the Local Planning Authority has first been sought and obtained.
*Using the most recent revision the of the Standard
** Plans must be of a minimum scale of 1:200 (unless otherwise agreed by the Local Planning Authority)

Reason:  To safeguard the future of  trees, hedges and shrubs in the interests of the visual amenities and the biodiversity value of the area and the setting and character of the proposed development in accordance with policies: 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015; 1.1(i) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); policy LV5.10 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013) and interim SPG 9: Trees and Development Guidelines.

| No development shall commence in relation to each phase of development (including initial site clearance) until a suitable programme of monitoring of all approved tree protection measures has been submitted and approved by the Local Planning Authority.  The monitoring programme shall include the following:
a.	Confirmation of who shall be the lead Arboriculturalist for the development.
b.	Confirmation of the Site Manager, key personnel, their key responsibilities and contact details.
c.	Details of induction procedures for all personnel in relation to Arboricultural matters.

d.	A detailed timetable of events concerning the approved tree protection plans, including; initial implementation of the protective measures, the final removal of the protective measures and any incursion/alterations to accommodate site specific construction/demolition procedures as approved in the Arboricultural Method Statement and the level of supervision required.
e.	Procedures for dealing with variations or non-approved incursions into the construction exclusion zones as detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement.
f.	Agreements of when site monitoring will take place with the local Tree Officer either by site meetings or by some other pre-arranged agreement.
g.	Post development assessment of the retained and planted trees and any necessary remedial action.
The programme of Arboricultural monitoring shall be undertaken in full compliance with the approved details.

Reason: To safeguard the future of  trees, hedges and shrubs in the interests of the visual amenities and the biodiversity value of the area and the setting and character of the proposed development in accordance with policies: 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015; 1.1(i) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); and policy LV5.10 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013) and interim SPG 9: Trees and Development Guidelines.

| Details of the noise mitigation measures for all habitable rooms located along Northfield Avenue shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of superstructure works for Blocks C1, C2, C3 and C4 of the approved development. The noise mitigation measures shall comply with the criteria specified in Ealing's (interim) SPG 10: Noise and Vibration and include details of measures with windows closed and other means of ventilation provided. The details as approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of any residential units in the relevant part of the development and thereafter retained as such.

Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2016); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG10: Noise and Vibration.

| Sound limiting insulation shall be installed between the approved community room and dwelling above the community room before the first occupation of the community room, to achieve an acoustic standard not exceeding NR 25 Leq 5mins, (octaves) or NR 20 Leq 5mins, (one-third octaves) inside a bedroom, and NR 30 Leq,5mins (octaves) or NR 25 Leq,5mins (one-third octaves) inside a living room when noise is generated from the community room.

Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2016); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG10: Noise and Vibration.

| The rating noise level emitted from the proposed plant and machinery, as assessed under BS4142: 1997, shall be lower than the existing background noise level by at least 5 dBA as measured at 3.5 m from the nearest ground floor sensitive facade and 1m from upper floor noise sensitive facades, during the relevant periods of operation.

Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2016); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG10: Noise and Vibration.

| Details of the scheme to provide fresh air ventilation to all habitable rooms located along Northfield Avenue shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval prior to the commencement of superstructure works for Blocks C1, C2, C3 and C4. The details as approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of any residential units in the relevant part of the development and thereafter retained as such.

Reason: The Air Quality Stage 4 Review and Assessment for the London Borough of Ealing has highlighted that this area currently experiences or is likely to experience exceedences of Government set air quality standards and air quality mitigation is required for those residential dwellings located within the Northfield Avenue building elevation. It is necessary that future occupiers are not exposed to poor air quality that could have a negative impact on health and as such, mitigation would be necessary in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan (2016); the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG (2014); policies 1.1(e) and (j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), and policy 7A of Ealing's adopted Development Management DPD (2013).

| Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), a soil contamination investigation and risk assessment for that relevant Phase of development shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The contamination investigation and risk assessment should include the following information:

a.	An intrusive ground investigation and risk assessment of the site shall be carried out in accordance with BS1075:2011+A1:2013 and CR11 guidance to assess the nature and extent of any contamination on the site. This assessment must be undertaken by a competent person, and shall assess any contamination on the site, whether or not it originates on the site;

b.	A contamination remediation scheme to bring the site to a condition suitable for the intended end use. It shall include all works to be undertaken, proposed remediation objectives and remediation criteria, timetable of works and site management procedures.  The scheme must ensure that the site will not qualify as contaminated land under Part 2A of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 in relation to the intended use of the land after remediation;

c.	Within 6-months of the completion of measures identified in the approved contamination remediation scheme, a verification report that demonstrates the effectiveness of the remediation carried out shall be produced and submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The verification report submitted shall be in accordance with the Environment Agency guidance 'Verification of Remediation of Land Contamination', Report: SC030114/R1'.

Reason: To protect the health and living conditions of residents in the area in accordance policies 2.7 and 4.1 of the Adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004), policy 1.1(e) of the Ealing Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), policy 5.21 of the London Plan (2016); policy LV5.21 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013); the National Planning Policy Framework (2012), and  DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'.

| The Surface Water Drainage Scheme shall be implemented and subsequently maintained in accordance with the details approved under discharge of condition reference number 160960CND dated 21st November 2016

Reason:  To minimise the risk of flooding, to improve and protect water quality, improve habitat and amenity and in the interests of the drainage network in accordance with policies 5.12, 5.13 and 5.14 of the London Plan (2016), policy 1.2(m) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.12 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013).

| Any additional capacity required in the Thames Water system, including any required suitable connection point to the Thames Water system shall be implemented and subsequently maintained in accordance with the details approved under discharge of condition reference number 160657CND dated 22nd April 2017.

Reason:  To ensure that the water supply infrastructure has sufficient capacity to cope with the additional demand, in accordance with policy 5.14 of the London Plan 2016; and policy 6.1 of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012.

| Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase of development (excluding site preparation and demolition), a piling risk assessment and method statement shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The piling risk assessment should demonstrate that the chosen method of piling would not increase the risk of near-surface pollutants migrating into deeper geological formations and aquifers. The Piling Method Statement should include details of the type of piling to be undertaken and the methodology by which such piling would be carried out, including measures to prevent and minimise the potential for damage to subsurface water or sewage infrastructure. The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: To ensure that any proposed piling methods do not pose a pollution risk to controlled waters, water or sewage infrastructure in accordance with policy 5.15 of the London Plan 2016, and policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012.
| The Energy Centre shall be implemented and subsequently maintained in accordance with the details approved under discharge of condition reference number 160958CND  dated 10th May 2016.

Reason: To secure the measures set out within the approved Energy Statement and to ensure that the energy plant room is designed in a manner which allows for the future connection to a district system and contributes to reducing the use of fossil fuel or other primary energy generation capacity, and to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases in accordance with policies 5.2, 5.3, 5.5, 5.6 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1(e), 1.1(j), 1.1(k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, policies LV5.2 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD, and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG.

| The approved development, excluding Block C4, shall incorporate measures to achieve an overall reduction in regulated CO2 emissions of at least 35.2% beyond Building Regulations Part L 2013 through the following carbon emission savings as detailed in the approved Sherwood Close Energy Statement D (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham and the approved Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessment Rev A (dated 27/10/2014), prepared by Max Fordham:
a.	energy saving measures to achieve at least 9% savings in regulated carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions beyond the complaint Building Regulations Part L 2013 base case;

b.	site-wide district heating network linking all new dwellings (with the exception of the eight (8) dwellinghouses in Block D) to achieve a reduction in regulated CO2 emissions of 6.4% over the 'Be Lean' stage.
c.	incorporation of solar PV technology to achieve at least a 23.9% savings (and equal to 104.2 tonnes CO2 / annum) in regulated carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions beyond the 'Be Clean' stage.

d.	use of Ultra low-NOx boilers with maximum NOx Emissions that are compliant with the NOx (g/m²) benchmarks set out at Appendix 5 of the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG for Class C3 land use class.

Within six-months of the first occupation of new dwellings in Phase 3 the Energy Performance Certificates and modelling output reports from the "as built stage" to confirm compliance of the 286 new dwellings in the approved development in terms of savings achieved through energy efficiency measures shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The approved measures shall be thereafter retained.

Reason: To secure the measures set out within the approved Energy Statement and Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessment and to ensure that the energy efficiency measures to be incorporated into the approved development contribute to reducing the use of fossil fuel or other primary energy generation capacity, and to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, and to minimise the impact of building emissions on local air quality in the interests of health, in accordance with policies 5.2, 5.3, 5.5, 5.6 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1(e), 1.1(j), 1.1(k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, policies LV5.2 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD, and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG.

| Details of the layout and array of photovoltaic panels, except for Block C4, which shall provide for no less than 104.2 tonnes CO2 emission savings / annum (equivalent to 23.9% on-site C02 reduction against the 'Be Clean' stage) as detailed within the approved Sherwood Close Energy Statement D, dated 27/10/2014, prepared by Max Fordham, shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval within 6 months of the commencement of the superstructure works for Phase 1 of the approved development. The approved layout and array of photovoltaic panels shall be retained in working order.

Reason:  In the interest of sustainable development and combating climate change in accordance with policies 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.7 and 7.4 of the London Plan 2016; policy 1.1(k) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy LV 5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013) and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG.

| Except for the new dwellings within Block C4, each new dwelling shall be constructed to achieve at least Level 4 of the Code for Sustainable Homes (based on November 2010 Technical Guide / Addendum 2014 for England Technical Guide).

Within three months of the commencement of the development on each Phase, evidence that the development is registered with the Building Research Establishment (BRE) (or similar approved body) under the Code for Sustainable Homes and an Interim Code for Sustainable Homes Assessment and Interim Design Certificates shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval.

Within three-months of the first occupation of each Phase of development, a Post-Construction Code for Sustainable Homes Assessment and Certificates verified by BRE (or similar approved body) confirming that the agreed sustainability measures have been implemented shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval and thereafter retained.

Reason: In the interest of addressing climate change and securing sustainable development in accordance with policies: 3.5, 5.1; 5.2; 5.3, 5.9 and 7.4 of the London Plan 2016; policies 1.1 (k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policies LV3.5 and LV5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG.

| Details and samples of all facing materials shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any work commencing on the superstructure of the relevant Phase of development. The samples and details shall include:
a.	brickwork (including brick panels and mortar courses);
b.	render (including details of colour and texture);
c.	cladding materials, including roof finishes;
d.	all window treatments (including sections and reveals);
e.	building entrance details and material samples;
f.	balcony structures and balustrading treatment (including sections);
g.	privacy screen treatment;
h.	sub-station, energy-centre, refuse and bicycle store entrance doors and ventilation louvres;
i.	entrance gates to off-street car parking areas;
j.	any other materials to be used.
The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved and thereafter retained.

Reason:  In the interest of securing sustainable development and to ensure that the resulting appearance of the development is of a high standard in accordance with policies: 3.5, 7.1, 7.4 and 7.6 of the London Plan (2016); 1.1(h), 1.1(k), 1.2(f), 1.2(h) and 2.10 of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); and policies LV3.5, LV7.4 and 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013).

| Notwithstanding the detailed landscaping and public realm proposals illustrated on the approved drawings, the Design & Access Statement and Biodiversity Survey and Report, further details of the landscaping proposals shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority within six (6) months of the commencement of each Phase of the development in respect of the following matters (and relating to the relevant Phase of development):
a.	Full details of the design of the children play areas, including safety surfacing and equipment (where relevant);

b.	Soft landscaping: including grass and turf areas, hedges, shrub and herbaceous areas, allotments and tree strategy including species type and size at planting. Tree species should include a palette of different species of trees in order to avoid streets and long sections of landscaping that are planted in monocultures;

c.	Hard landscaping: including ground surfaces, kerbs, edges, ridge and flexible paving, seating or other public realm furniture, steps, and any synthetic surfaces and a drawing illustrating the Local Highways Authority adoption boundary;
d.	Enclosures and boundary treatments, including types, dimensions and finishes of walls, fences, screen walls, barriers, bollards, rails, retaining walls and hedges;

e.	A statement detailing how the landscaping proposals contribute to the mitigation measures for nesting birds, the enablement of species to migrate such as hedgehogs and other small mammals through gaps in fencing and ecological enhancements detailed within the approved Biodiversity Survey and Report, including the number and location of swift boxes, sparrow terrace, bat bricks, bee boxes and other measures to enhance ecology (as relevant);

f.	Details of the location of the 540 sq.m of green roofs and 2484 sq.m of brown roofs and details of the seed mix, substrate base, depth of soil or growing medium, and drainage / irrigation systems for these areas;
g.	Work phasing plan.

Any trees or shrubs that die within five years of planting shall be replaced with the same species of the same size or an approved alternative and to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority during the next planting season.

The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved plans and details. Boundary treatments shall be fully provided before the first occupation of the part of development which it forms part. The approved details shall be retained thereafter.

Reason: To ensure the approved landscaping and play areas are provided as an integral feature of the development and that all such landscaping, boundary treatments and street furniture is retained in the interests of the setting of the buildings and visual amenities of the locality; to provide biodiversity within the site and to ensure that the use of mains water in the landscape areas is reduced through the incorporation of rainwater harvesting technologies; in accordance with policies 5.10, 5.15, 7.4, 7.5 and 7.21 of the London Plan (2016); policies 1.1(e), 1.1(h) and 1.1(i) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); and policy LV5.10 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013).

| Within six months of the commencement of development on each Phase of development, details of the bicycle storage enclosures for the dwellings within the relevant Phase of development and the visitor spaces associated with the 70 sq.m community room shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The submission of details in relation to Phase 2 of the approved development should incorporate enhanced security measures for the bicycle storage facilities located in Block B5 due to the large number of bicycles to be stored in this area. The enhanced security measures should be discussed with the Crime Prevention Design Officer prior to the submission of the details to the Local Planning Authority.

The submission of details in relation to Block C4 should include the provision of secure and covered bicycle storage facilities with capacity for at least 56 bicycles, including exploring the opportunities to provide 5% of stands to be able to accommodate larger cycles and the bicycle storage facilities shall be retained as approved thereafter.
